Slightly off-topic, but: There's actually no such thing as a non-virtual override. In your class `B`, both `methodA1` and `methodA2` are virtual overrides. 

Given:
```c++
struct A {
    virtual void foo();
}
struct B : A {
    // <insert code here>
}
```
there are 4 equivalent ways of writing the override:
```c++
virtual void foo(); // usual C++98 style
void foo(); // not the usual style, but equivalent to the previous line
            // --> the `virtual` keyword is not required in derived classes
virtual void foo() override; // C++11, functionally equivalent but compiler will 
                             // throw an error if the base function is not virtual
void foo() override; // recommended C++11 style, works just like the previous line
```
The only difference between the 4 lines is that `override` will help catch some mistakes at compile time. The last line is the recommended style by the [C++ Core Guidelines](https://github.com/isocpp/CppCoreGuidelines/blob/master/CppCoreGuidelines.md#c128-virtual-functions-should-specify-exactly-one-of-virtual-override-or-final): "Virtual functions should specify exactly one of `virtual`, `override`, or `final`".

